<heading box="[457,924,614,638]" centered="true" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" reason="7">
<taxonomicName authority="Han &amp; Galsworthy &amp; Xue, 2009" authorityName="Han &amp; Galsworthy &amp; Xue" authorityYear="2009" box="[457,685,614,638]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Geometra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burmensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[457,685,614,638]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Geometra burmensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[694,785,614,638]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation box="[801,915,614,638]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="7.[213,280,1415,1437]" captionTargetBox="[213,1159,169,1350]" captionTargetId="figure-20@7.[212,1169,167,1350]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 1. Adults of Geometra. (A) G. papilionaria, „; (B) G. symaria, „; (C) G. albovenaria, „; (D) G. valida, „; (E) G. euryagyia, „; (F) G. dieckmanni, „; (G) G. sponsaria, „; (H) G. ussuriensis, „; (I) G. neovalida sp. nov. „, holotype; (J) G. flavifrontaria, „; (K) G. purissima, „, holotype; (L) G. smaragdus, „; (M) G. fragilis, „, syntype; (N) G. sinoisaria, „, syntype; (O) G. burmensis sp. nov., „, holotype; (P) G. glaucaria, „; (Q) G. rana, „; (R) G. sigaria, „, syntype. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5216167" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5216167/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Figure 1O</figureCitation>
)
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="916" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,340,694,718]" box="[213,340,694,718]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis box="[213,340,694,718]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,1169,734,885]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Antennae in male bipectinate, tapered towards end, the longest ramus more than three times the diameter of flagellum. Frons yellow, probably faded from green. Labial palpus yellowish brown, probably faded from dark green, only slightly extending beyond frons. Vertex greenish-white. Dorsal side of thorax green. Hind tibia without hair-pencil.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,1169,936,1151]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis box="[213,359,936,960]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Wing pattern</emphasis>
. Length of forewing 
<emphasis box="[600,618,936,959]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">„</emphasis>
<quantity box="[618,736,936,960]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" unit="mm" value="21.0" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="20.0">20–22 mm</quantity>
. Wings yellowish green. Outer margin of both wings smooth, no tail process on hindwing. Forewing with apex slightly falcate; antemedial line white, wavy, strongly curved outwards between lower margin of cell and vein A 
<subScript attach="left" box="[421,431,1042,1058]" fontSize="7" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">2</subScript>
. Postmedial line of both wings white, nearly straight, indistinct near costa. Submarginal line composed of white patches between veins. Discal spot invisible. Fringes green basally and white terminally. Underside greenish white, postmedial line visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,1169,1201,1480]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis box="[213,380,1201,1225]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[402,529,1201,1225]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="8.[146,213,1651,1673]" captionTargetBox="[149,1103,165,1612]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[146,1103,165,1615]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 2. Male genitalia of Geometra. (A) G. papilionaria; (B) G. symaria; (C) G. albovenaria; (D) G. valida; (E) G. euryagyia; (F) G. dieckmanni; (G) G. sponsaria; (H) G. ussuriensis; (I) G." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5216169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5216169/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Figures 2O</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[547,584,1201,1225]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[146,213,1433,1455]" captionTargetBox="[146,1090,173,1396]" captionTargetId="figure-20@10.[146,1103,167,1397]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Aedeagus of Geometra. (A) G. papilionaria; (B) G. symaria; (C) G. albovenaria; (D) G. valida; (E) G. euryagyia; (F) G. dieckmanni; (G) G. sponsaria; (H) G. ussuriensis; (I) G. neovalida sp. nov.; (J) G. flavifrontaria; (K) G. purissima; (L) G. smaragdus; (M) G. fragilis; (N) G. sinoisaria; (O) G. burmensis sp. nov.; (P) G. glaucaria; (Q) G. rana; (R) G. sigaria. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5216171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5216171/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">3O</figureCitation>
). Uncus sclerotized, triangular. Socii sclerotized, curved and tapered. Gnathos developed, median area expanded, with a pair of short, pointed processes. Valva with basal half broad, tapered towards end. Spinose patch present, distally from which is a pointed harpe located on a transverse sclerotized ridge. Saccus developed, protruding, blunt. Transtilla undeveloped. Juxta membranous. Aedeagus sclerotized posteriorly and tapered.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,1169,1201,1480]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">
Sternite 3 without setal patches. Segment 8 (
<figureCitation box="[775,889,1392,1416]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="12.[146,213,831,853]" captionTargetBox="[148,1106,169,793]" captionTargetId="figure-270@12.[146,1097,167,787]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 5. Segment 8 of Geometra. (A) G. papilionaria; (B) G. symaria; (C) G. albovenaria; (D) G. valida; (E) G. euryagyia; (F) G. dieckmanni; (G) G. sponsaria; (H) G. ussuriensis; (I) G. neovalida sp. nov.; (J) G. flavifrontaria; (K) G. purissima; (L) G. smaragdus; (M) G. fragilis; (N) G. sinoisaria; (O) G. burmensis sp. nov.; (P) G. glaucaria; (Q) G. rana; (R) G. sigaria." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5216175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5216175/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Figure 5O</figureCitation>
) with tergite sclerotized posteriorly, with posterior margin shallowly depressed at middle and expanded laterally; sternite deeply depressed at middle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,535,1536,1560]" box="[213,535,1536,1560]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis box="[213,397,1536,1560]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Female genitalia</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,322,1611,1635]" box="[213,322,1611,1635]" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis box="[213,322,1611,1635]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[213,1169,1650,1706]" lastBlockId="32.[146,1103,168,322]" lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="916" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Han &amp; Galsworthy &amp; Xue" authorityYear="2009" box="[213,438,1650,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Geometra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burmensis">
<emphasis box="[213,438,1650,1674]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">Geometra burmensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is broadly similar externally to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1880" box="[799,950,1650,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Tanaorhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="smaragdus">
<emphasis box="[799,950,1650,1674]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">G. smaragdus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but much smaller, and the antemedial and postmedial lines of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Han &amp; Galsworthy &amp; Xue" authorityYear="2009" box="[730,876,1682,1706]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Geometra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="915" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burmensis">
<emphasis box="[730,876,1682,1706]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="915">G. burmensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not accompanied by shading as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1880" box="[303,455,169,193]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Tanaorhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="916" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="smaragdus">
<emphasis box="[303,455,169,193]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="916">G. smaragdus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the male genitalia, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Han &amp; Galsworthy &amp; Xue" authorityYear="2009" box="[719,863,169,193]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Geometra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="916" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burmensis">
<emphasis box="[719,863,169,193]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="916">G. burmensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oberthur" authorityYear="1916" box="[991,1103,169,193]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Hipparchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="916" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fragilis">
<emphasis box="[991,1103,169,193]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="916">G. fragilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[198,340,201,225]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Geometra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="916" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinoisaria">
<emphasis box="[198,340,201,225]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="916">G. sinoisaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the setae on the valvae are less developed than in those two species. The new species is distinctive in its gnathos, which is expanded in the middle and carries a pair of slender, curved processes: in 
<taxonomicName box="[703,842,266,290]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Geometra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="916" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinoisaria">
<emphasis box="[703,842,266,290]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="916">G. sinoisaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the gnathos is a simple solid process, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oberthur" authorityYear="1916" box="[408,521,298,322]" class="Insecta" family="Lepidoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Hipparchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="916" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fragilis">
<emphasis box="[408,521,298,322]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="916">G. fragilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the gnathos carries a pair of thorn-like processes.
</paragraph>
